strategy for raising the full-cell discharge potential. However,
in the case of the ZFO-200/LFP-CNT cell, when the load is
increased, the average voltage drops to values comparable (and
even lower) to those of the ZFO-deLi/LFP-CNT cell.
Although it might appear surprising, this is a direct conse-
quence of the previously mentioned incomplete utilization of
the cathode material in the ZFO-deLi/LFP-CNT cell caused by
the limiting anode during discharge. As a matter of fact, the
positive electrode voltage does not approach its lower limit
during the cell discharge (see left plot in Figure 3 c). This cor-
responds to a higher average cell voltage, but lower capacity.
For the cell containing the ZFO-200 negative electrode, both
electrodes are approaching their full discharge (center plot of
Figure 3 c) and thus the LFP-CNT electrode voltage is steeply
decreasing toward the end of the discharge. This means that
the average voltage of the LFP electrode is lower than in the
previous cell, which results in a lower average cell voltage. The
